data.review_text: Great Location. Awesome views. That’s where the greatness ends. ||The hotel is very tired. I would imagine in its prime this hotel was beautiful but it is in desperate need of a refurb and clean. The bathroom looked older than me. Lots of mould and mildew. The bedroom was tiny but we expected this. The view was spectacular. The heating wasn’t the best the room got to an ok temperature but never toasty. The bed was comfortable and the bedding was clean. I wouldnt have minded the tiredness of the hotel so much had we not paid so much for the room. We only slept and showered in the room so it really wasn’t the end of the world for us it was simply the cost of the hotel and what we received were exceptionally poor considering the standard we are used to in other hotels we have stayed at across the USA. We won’t be returning to the New Yorker but we will certainly be back in New York again!

I booked this hotel for a Christmas stay with my boyfriend. The location itself is worth the price alone, which is why we booked. But I must say, upon arrival I was pleasantly surprised by the appearance and the kindness of the staff. Thank you to Lynn, who helped us check in. Without even asking, she set us up with an early check in and a better room. She was super quick and efficient and so helpful. The ambience and the staff make the great location even better!! Will definitely be staying again.

Great hotel for a great price! I went to a show at MSG and it was directly across the street! Couldn’t be easier! It’s not a fancy updated hotel, but I loved the art deco interior! It was clean and felt extremely safe. Would definitely recommend, especially if going to MSG. Parking is across the street as well and they do luggage storage if you are wanting to explore NYC before heading home! Great NYC hotel overall!

really nice hotel right by all the attractions. The rooms were big and spacious and with comfy beds, Very clean and tidy. The concierge was really good and very helpful. full of good tips and also got me a taxi instantly. Would stay here again for sure

Third time here but the 1st for my granddaughter. I've always loved the art deco decor which she thought was Very Fancy! Praise indeed from a 15 y.o.! Her eyes opened even wider when she got to the room......as we had arrived early our room wasn't ready, but the excellent Mohammed at reception offered us a free upgrade to a room that was ready- a 2 bed, 2 bathroom.  His fantastic service for very welcome by 2 weary travellers and the lovely beds with the fluffiest pillows meant we got a quick nap b4 heading over to Madison Sq Gdns to watch the ice hockey. That's the other great thing about the hotel- it's location. It's less than 10 mins from the Empire State Building, Times Sq and Macys and 2 mins to Penn Station which takes you most everywhere else. Will definitely rebook there for my next trip!

Great location with a great view from the room, but the room was a little bit small.  We were able to check in early which was really great, but when we asked if one of the staff could take a picture with their Christmas tree, we were told that he couldn't and he didn't offer to have any of the other numerous staff help.  The central spinning door was out of service for some portion of our stay.  On checkout our room keys stopped working early which is something I've seen at many hotels and given that both keys stopped working I have to imagine is intentional.  This almost made us miss our train, and while it was resolved fairly quickly there was a stressful moment trying to let the clerks understand that we really did need service right now.  I admit our fault for running so late, but there is no excuse for a key to stop working while it belongs to a room we have paid for either.

Exceeded my expectations.  For the price and location I'll stay here again and again.  The room was larger than many NYC hotel rooms I've stayed in.  I didn't mind the vintage nostalgia of the decor and bathroom fixtures either....it was squeaky clean and that's what matters.   Had no issues with noise whatsoever on 28th floor, and a great view with a slice of the river in view as well!  I appreciated the added safety procedure of having to show your room card to get to the elevators.  All of the staff were friendly and helpful.

Mohammed was so nice and accommodating he made us feel so comfortable!  He explained everything to us and made special arrangements for us.  ||We had a corner room that was very large with a queen size bed. Everything was wonderful!  Next time we come to New York, we’ll definitely stay at the New Yorker!

Had a room with a view. Didn't know what to expect and was pleasantly surprised with a view of the Empire State building. Rooms are a little tired deco wise but it's a old hotel. The housekeeping kept the rooms clean and replenished towels daily. Felt very secure with doormen checking guests for they room keys before entering. Overall, really happy with the location of the hotel, walking distance from Penn station and Macys, the staff and service we received staying at the Wyndham New Yorker

The biggest selling point of the hotel is location- very convenient to everywhere in midtown and it neighbors a big train station. The hotel has a 3 star lobby but maybe a 2 star room. The room was outdated - the bathroom was extremely small, you have to close the door to be able to sit on the toilet. The sink was very small and no place for any of your personal care items, you will worry about hitting your head when wash your face. If you have to book it, ask for a very high floor - I found that the high floor is helpful from eliminating noise perception. The receptionists service is difficult to describe, quite often there is no body there - they seemed like to go back to a room behind the counter, which is a bit annoying, but once you called them and they are there, they are friendly.

Quite old, not particularly clean hotel. Rooms are small and in average to poor conditions. I wasn't expecting it. Pictures on their website are very different respect to the reality. A refurbishment is needed as soon as possible.

However, beds and pillows were so comfortable. 5 star level, honestly. I slept like a baby.

Therefore, I'm giving a 4 out 5.

Rooms (and Queen beds) are a little on the small side. Otherwise, this hotel is perfect. It's got a lot of art-deco charm, a great location, and a wonderful 24-hr diner on site. What a great place to stay! One of our windows had a perfect view of the Empire State Building!

If you're going to an event at MSG this is your place. 1 1/2 block away. Hotel and rooms are clean. Rooms/bathroom are dated but quiet and clean but need modernization. There are several restaurants inside the hotel, including a 24/7 diner which is super convenient. Have stayed at the New Yorker before and will again but wish Hyatt would update the rooms and hallways.

Although on the surface, the lead you see in advertisements looks too good to be true, you can rest assured it's even worse than you might imagine. Wyndham uses a partner called Monster Resort Group to market their "discounted getaways" which are a front for timeshare presentations and high pressure sales. ||The ads advertise a 5 day/4 night stay at a hotel in NYC and range from $199 to a low of ~$30 if you fill out a demographic survey in advance. But this is only the beginning. Once you enter your credit card info and your personal information, you'll be subject to multiple pop ups that try to upsell you on an extra night, daily breakfast and even a close in 7 day booking window...all without confirming that your hotel is available for the dates you would like (although the ad says the dates are highly flexible).||Once you wade through this mire and opt in for what you'd like, you get both a text and email letting you know you've been charged and providing you with instructions on how to contact the Monster Resort Group to look at initial availability. On the first call, before being transferred to someone who could help book me into the NYC hotel, I was upsold for $299 for 1-2 additional vacations, which I declined. My membership now "activated", I was transferred to what they represented as a hotel booking line. In reality, it's just another Monster employee. ||You're given the opportunity to book through an online portal, but even if it shows availability for the dates you'd like (and there is only 3-4 months of availability shown from hotels, all dates more than that are blocked), you must first verify with the Monster employee that the dates are still available in their database, then they will reach out to the actual hotel to confirm they can accommodate you, meaning that only during low demand periods will there be any availability. ||In a nutshell, Monster is selling excess capacity at these hotels -- rooms that would go vacant if not for people responding to the ads and buying the "discounted getaways". Any room you receive will be the most basic that the hotel has. AND you'll be subject to a $175 deposit/ransom fee in advance to ensure you attend the mandatory timeshare presentation which is several subway stops away from the hotel, as well as the customary ~$200 security hold on your credit card for the room upon check in.||If you are able to book your stay at the hotel, then the real high pressure sales start. I was immediately told that I was in a standard room, but I could upgrade for $29/night with a promise of a city view. The upgraded room was deplorable: tiny, no coffee maker/mini fridge as promised, and a view of a brick wall, even though an enhanced view was promised with the upgrade. It took a whole day and three customer service agents to get this resolved...they only took it seriously after I asked for my upgrade fee back. ||The timeshare presentation, billed as 90-120 minutes ran long and required a bit of time to get to on the subway...it was not close to the hotel at all. Although the salesperson stressed that multiple annual vacations could be taken with the timeshare plan he was selling, that's only true if you want to vacation at mid tier properties; to book a week in NYC or Hawaii, you either have to pay more annually or save up your points for multiple years. In addition to annual membership fees, there are annual upkeep fees and an initial initiation fee...so it all adds up. ||There are multiple managers / supervisors who pop into the presentations to "check in" and help close the deals, they reduced the total costs four times during the presentation, a couple of times just discounting the plan they were trying to sell, a couple of times downsizing the plan (i.e. fewer annual points to use at a lower cost) -- but that means even more time in between vacations to places you'd actually want to go. ||My biggest issue with this program is not the inflated prices, but rather the underhanded way that the third party (Monster Resort Group) hides charges and fees and misrepresents their ability to find you the hotel rooms during the time you want. When I brought this up to the Wyndham timeshare sales team, they just shrugged, said they'd heard it before, and indicated they weren't able to control what 3rd party vendors did or said. ||Best advice: consider all the true costs of these offers. These include not only the upfront charge, but all the upsells you'd want to make your stay a pleasant one and the time & energy you'll need to spend talking/negotiating/arguing with all the people involved in the sales process.

We had an amazing weekend stay at the New Yorker. We arrived early at 9 a.m. on Friday and asked about the possibility of an early check-in. The front desk staff was incredibly friendly, and for a small fee, we were upgraded to a two-room suite and were able to check in right away. Shortly after settling in, the staff called to ensure everything was satisfactory and even extended our check-out time by an hour at no extra cost. The rooms have a charming vintage feel, which we loved, and the beds—including the sofa bed—were exceptionally comfortable. Every staff member, from security to the concierge to the TikTok diner team, was so helpful and kind. The location was ideal, within walking distance to Broadway, Times Square, the Empire State Building, Penn Station, and the bus terminal, with a subway station conveniently next to the hotel. We will definitely be returning in the future!

My daughter and I went to NYC to celebrate her birthday. We stayed at the New Yorker Hotel. Driss, the gentleman who checked us in couldn’t have been more welcoming or accommodating. He didn’t have any rooms with a view the day we checked in, but the next day he surprised us with a room with a spectacular view of the Empire State Building.I want to recognize him because he went above and beyond to make our stay special.

My fiancé and I stayed at the New Yorker for a week's vacation in July. We requested a room with a view which we discovered later was just a room on a higher floor (no particular view of any special land marks). We stayed at the hotel with two other couples (all in our own rooms) and all found it was a great "base" to start/end our days or meet up throughout our activities. We were able to check in about two hours early with no extra charge which was very appreciated after a long morning of travelling. The hotel was in a fantastic location, right across the street from Penn Station which was excellent for first-time visitors to NYC. The hotel is in an extremely walkable area, a few minutes walk from Broadway, Times Square, and several attractions that we visited. The rooms were small and the bathroom was quite old and that is my reason for deducting one star. At the end of the day, we really just needed a bed to sleep on and a bathroom to shower but having a bit more space would have been appreciated so that we didn't have to live out of our suitcases for the week! Also, something like a mini fridge would be huge for guests of this hotel as we visited in the hot summer and cold drinks are a must. The ice bucket was tiny (room for two bottles of soda/water) and I would have preferred a more convenient way to have a cool drink without having to go to CVS and buy them. I do believe I would stay here again due to the convenience of location, but would be open to other options for sure as the amenities were not as up-to-date as I think they could have been.

My recent stay at The New Yorker Hotel was a mixed experience, with both positives and significant drawbacks. Let me start by addressing the issues I encountered. I came back to the hotel and had trouble with my room key card not working. When I approached the front desk, Vanessa, the receptionist, was extremely rude and uncooperative. What should have been a quick 10-second fix turned into a 45-minute wait, making the quick fix process unnecessarily frustrating and unwelcoming. Her behavior stood in stark contrast to the rest of the staff, who were all warm and accommodating.

The condition of the bathroom was another major disappointment. The facility is quite dated, which could be charming in a classic hotel, but the quality was poor. The water was discolored and brown, and the sink failed to drain properly, with water pooling up every time it was used. It certainly didn't meet basic standards of cleanliness and functionality.

On the positive side, the hotel’s old classic theme and décor do give it a unique charm, reminiscent of New York’s bygone era. The ambiance is elegant and has a historic appeal that’s worth appreciating. Additionally, aside from my encounter with Vanessa, the other staff members were friendly and made an effort to make the stay enjoyable.

In summary, while the hotel has a nostalgic character and friendly staff, my experience was overshadowed by poor service from a specific employee and maintenance issues in the bathroom. There’s potential for a great stay here, but significant improvements are needed.

Brilliant location for everything you need to do, rooms very basic. Staff are lovely and always want to help, reception is beautiful I just don’t understand what’s happened to the rest of the hotel. Rooms are clean just very tired. However it works so well with being so close to the trains and stations.

Rooms are a little tired but still have everything you need. Bathroom a little tired but everything worked well.  We had a 2 bed room on 22nd floor which had a view of the Empire State Building which was nice. Enough room/space in the room with extra spare towels.  Fast lifts down - staff all friendly.  Good location to get anywhere really either by foot or public transport.
